result.execSummary:
The defendant Jessica A Lang was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Possess Firearm-Convicted of a Felony, a class G felony, Wisconsin Statutes 941.29(1m)(a).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

superMiscConds.notes: Same conditions as outlined for probation.

miscConds.notes: If probation or extended supervision is revoked or will discharge with outstanding financial obligations due, a civil judgment shall be entered for the balance due.
Defendant shall not possess any dangerous weapons.

Defendant shall not possess or consume alcohol, controlled substances or drug paraphernalia without a valid prescription. 
Defendant shall not associate with known drug users or be present where drugs are purchased, used, stored, packaged or distributed. 
Defendant shall not enter any establishment where the primary purpose is the sale or service of alcohol.
Defendant shall not work in a liquor store, bar or tavern.

Defendant shall pay Dept of Corrections supervision fees. 
Defendant shall participate in an AODA assessment and all counseling or treatment programs as directed by her supervising agent. 
Defendant shall provide a biological specimen for DNA analysis. Defendant has the right to request expungement of DNA analysis in writing through the Department of Justice.
Defendant shall maintain absolute sobriety.
Defendant shall obtain and maintain full time employment or school or a combination thereof.
